{
  "text": "Finally, the departure criterion for spin prediction is set as the first time that the AOS surpasses AE10 when the AOA is higher than [CITATION_1] , before developed spin. Flight test results indicate that the model spins shortly after it surpasses the given criteria. The flight data of , , r from six spins are shown in Figure 13 , and spin prediction is flagged with vertical lines in black, where air data parameters surpass the criterion. Meanwhile, the spin entry points are temporarily defined as r spin =2 \u00f0100 =s\u00de (average yaw rate at developed spin), flagged with vertical lines in red, in order to provide a time reference. It can be inferred from the diagrams that spins 1, 3, 5 present rapid spin entry with a fast rising AOA, and further the AOS reaches a prediction criterion when > 40 , \u00bc 10 , followed by spin entry in a half second. In contrast, the deviation of flow angles change smoothly in spins 2, 4, 6, and the prediction flags are ahead of spin entry by 0.9 s $ 1.7 s. In addition, the wing rock is observed during this time. Compared with inertial parameters, the air data reflects the incipient spin stage earlier. It can be seen that black vertical lines occur at the beginning of yaw rate rising or shortly before its rising. Although it is only hundreds of milliseconds in advance, it is possible for automatic recovery systems to engage a maneuver. Moreover, the control surfaces are effective at the prediction time when the AOA is not too high, which is beneficial to the recovery. Moreover, the air data and inertial data will be combined to make the prediction more reliable and robust. Further, an automatic spin recovery controller will be designed, which is able to respond at the beginning of spin entry, applicable for both manned and unmanned aircraft, reducing the risk of spinning.",
